@NODE "Requirements"
REQUIREMENTS
============

GSD needs the reqtools.library and AmigaOS 2.0 or better.
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Concept and definitions"
CONCEPT AND DEFINITIONS
=======================

The operation of the algorithms is illustrated by sorting "elements".
Each element has a "position" and a "value". The elements are
represented in an array (called A in the following) with indices
going from 1 to 72. A position corresponds to the index in the array
A, a value to the number stored at this position. E.g. A[13]=42
means that the element at position 13 has a value of 42. The values
can reach form 1 to 72. The array is sorted in ascending order, so
that in the end A[1] <= A[2] <= ... <= A[72].

Sorting can be divided mainly into two different operations: the
"comparison" and the "moving" of elements. During a comparison the
values of two elements are compared using one of the relations <, >,
<= or >=. Moving again can be divided into two different operations:
"exchanging" and "shifting". During an exchange the values of two
elements are exchanged. This takes three basic operations (t:=A[p1];
A[p1]:=A[p2]; A[p2]:=t). Shifting means to move an element from its
old position to a new position and to shift all elements between these
positions one place towards the old position. The expenditure for this
depends on the incrementation (i.e. the difference between old and new
position). The number of basic operations necessary is
incrementation+2 (first the element must be removed, then the elements
between old and new position are shifted one position and at last the
element is inserted at its new position; strictly speaking only values
are changed, not positions).
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Starting the program"
STARTING THE PROGRAM
====================

You can start GSD from CLI/shell or workbench. When starting from shell,
you can use the following template:

  CSM=CHOOSESCREENMODE/S,UDS=USEDEFAULTSCREEN/S

The switches have the following meaning:
  CSM: The program opens a screenmode requester, which lets you choose
       the screen mode for the GSD screen.
  UDS: The GSD window is opened on your default screen, GSD doesn't
       open an own screen for its window. Note: your screen must be
       large enough to display the GSD window and should have at least
       8 colors (though this is not tested by the program).
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Displays"
DISPLAYS
========

The displays are on the left side of the GSD window. Here you find:

@{" The sorting field   " LINK "The sorting field"}
@{" The status display  " LINK "The status display"}
@{" The info display    " LINK "The info display"}
@{" The counter display " LINK "The counter display"}
@ENDNODE


@NODE "The sorting field"
The sorting field
-----------------
This is the most important display of the program. Here all elements
are displayed graphically. The position of an item in the array A
corresponds to the (horizontal) position in the sorting field, i.e.
the item with index 1 is displayed near the left border, the item
with index 72 appears at the right border. The value of an element
corresponds to its "height" in the appropriate display (the height
of the point or the column or the length of the bar).  Elements which
are in the "wrong" place, are depicted black, elements which are in
the "correct" place (in accordance with the sorted order), are
depicted grey.
@ENDNODE


@NODE "The status display"
The status display
------------------
This display shows, what the program is currently doing (or not
doing ;-).
@ENDNODE


@NODE "The info display"
The info display
----------------
Here you can find additional information about the sorting process
(e.g. name of the sorting algorithm currently running).
@ENDNODE


@NODE "The counter display"
The counter display
-------------------
GSD has four counters, which count the number of operations described
above. Note: these numbers reflect only a "relative" truth. Don't use
them to make inference about the efficiency of the algorithms (see
above)!
@{b}Comparisons:@{ub} counts the number of comparisons.
@{b}Exchanges:@{ub} counts the number of exchanges.
@{b}Shifts:@{ub} counts the number of shift operations.
@{b}Moved elements:@{ub} counts the number of elements moved during exchanges
  and shifts. As described above, three moves are necessary for an
  exchange. The number of movements for a shift is distance + 2, where
  distance:=ABS(oldPosition-newPosition).
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Using the gadgets"
USING THE GADGETS
=================

Use the gadgets on the right side of the window to control the program
and to change some settings.

@{" Choosing an algorithm           " LINK "Choosing an algorithm"}
@{" Controlling the sorting process " LINK "Controlling the sorting process"}
@{" Controlling the display         " LINK "Controlling the display"}
@{" Manipulating the elements       " LINK "Manipulating the elements"}
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Choosing an algorithm"
Choosing an algorithm
---------------------
Use the cycle gadget on the top right to choose an algorithm. Eleven
algorithms are available, which are described briefly in the
following. See the @{"references" LINK "References"} for a more detailed description.
- @{b}Bubblesort:@{ub} A simple algorithm which brings the smallest element of
    the unsorted part of the array to its final position by multiple
    exchanges. See @{"[3]" LINK "References"}.
- @{b}Heapsort:@{ub} This algorithm uses the data structure "heap". In phase 1
    the heap is built and in phase 2 each time the larges element is
    removed from the heap and the heap structure is rebuilt. The heap
    is represented in the array A. The root is at position 1, the
    children of a NODE i are at positions 2*i and 2*i+1.
    For (re)building the heap structure a top-down strategy is used.
    The algorithm could be improved by using a bottom-up strategy,
    however this would require more complex operations than "shift"
    and "exchange" and thus cannot be handled by GSD. See @{"[1]" LINK "References"} and @{"[3]" LINK "References"}
    for further information.
- @{b}Insertionsort (binary):@{ub} Here the position for inserting an element
    is dertermined by binary search on the sorted part of the array.
- @{b}Insertionsort (straight):@{ub} This is a implementation of insertion sort
    with a linear search on the sorted part of the array.
- @{b}Mergesort (bottom up):@{ub} The idea behind merge sort is that two
    already sorted series are merged into one (sorted). This can be
    done very efficiently with the use of a secondary array, so that
    the elements are moved between theese arrays. However, GSD can
    display only one array, so the merging is done "in situ" with only
    one array (which is, of corse, not very efficient). Here two
    series are merged by first comparing the smallest elemensts of
    each serie. If the left element is smaller, it is already at the
    correct position. If the element at the right is smaller it is
    inserted left from the left element by a shift operation.
    This bottom-up version of mergesort is non-recursive. In step 1
    series of length 1 are sorted (i.e. sorted series of length 2 are
    produced), in each of the following steps the length is doubled.
    See @{"[3]" LINK "References"} for further information.
- @{b}Mergesort (top down):@{ub} This is a recursive mergesort implementation.
    The (partial) array is divided into two parts of (approximately)
    equal length. Both parts are sorted recursively and merged
    afterwards. Furthermore the general statements from above about
    the mergesort implementation apply. Also see @{"[3]" LINK "References"}.
- @{b}Quicksort:@{ub} This is a implementation of C.A.R. Hoare's quicksort. The
    critical point here is how to choose the partitioning element. The
    present implementation chooses the element in position (l+r)/2
    (rounded) for partitioning the partial array A[l..r]. The value of
    this element is not stored for further comparisons. Instead,
    elements are compared directly with the partitioning element
    thereby making theese comparisons visible (note that this is not
    an efficient implementation).
- @{b}Radixsort:@{ub} This sorting method differs from all other algorithms
    discussed here, because radix sort doesn't compare elements
    directly, but just looks at single bits of the values of the
    elements.
    This is a recursive implementation of the algorithm. First the
    highest relevant bit of all element values is checked (with 72
    elements this is bit number seven for the right). Elements with
    this bit set go to the right, all other elements go to the left
    (as with quicksort this is done by exchanging two elements). The
    left and right parts are sorted recursively using the next lower
    bit for checking. The examination of a bit is counted as a
    comparison and displayed accordingly.
    Sedgewick @{"[3]" LINK "References"} gives a non-recursive implementation of radix sort,
    which is, however, not suitable for a presentation in the present
    framework. Also see @{"[2]" LINK "References"}.
- @{b}Selectionsort:@{ub} Another simple sorting algorithm, which searches for
    the smallest element of the unsorted part and puts it to its
    correct position using an exchange operation.
- @{b}Shakersort:@{ub} This is an improved bubblesort, which alternatly brings
    the smallest and biggest element of the unsorted part to its
    correct position by multiple exchanges.
    See @{"[4]" LINK "References"} and @{"[2]" LINK "References"} ("cocktail-shaker sort").
- @{b}Shellsort:@{ub} This is the sorting algorithm developed by D.L. Shell.
    The program uses the increment sequence 40, 13, 4, 1 which was
    proposed by Knuth @{"[2]" LINK "References"}.
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Controlling the sorting process"
Controlling the sorting process
-------------------------------
@{b}Run:@{ub} starts the sorting process.
@{b}Pause:@{ub} stops the sorting process temporarily. It can be resumed by
  clicking this gadget again (or by clicking the Run-gadget).
  Additionally you can change directly into the step mode (see below).
@{b}Step:@{ub} change into step mode or execute the next step if the program
  already is in step mode (or in pause mode). A "step" includes all
  operations up to the next compare or move operation, i.e. the
  program stops at the next comparison or move (and displays it).
@{b}Stop:@{ub} this terminates the sorting process, which then cannot be
  resumed at the termination point. Only a complete new start (using
  the Run-gadget) is possible.
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Controlling the display"
Controlling the display
-----------------------
@{b}Compare Delay:@{ub} adjusts how long the program waits after the comparison
  of elements. The value indicates the time in 1/50 seconds.
@{b}Move Delay:@{ub} this is the corresponding waiting period after moving
  elements.
@{b}Show comp.?:@{ub} the program displays a comparison by depicting the
  compared elements red. With this gadget you can swith on and off
  this display.
@{b}Show move.?:@{ub} as above, but for moving elements. Exchanged elements are
  depicted yellow. During a shift operation the element to be shifted
  is depicted green, the other elements (which must be moved one
  position to the right) are depicted yellow.
@{b}Elements shown as:@{ub} the elements can be represented in three different
  types: points, columns or bars. Switching is possible even when the
  sorting process is running.
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Manipulating the elements"
Manipulating the elements
-------------------------
@{b}Store:@{ub} stores the element positions in a buffer.
@{b}Restore:@{ub} puts the elements back in the positions they had at time of
  last storing.
@{b}Sort:@{ub} sorts the elements directly.
@{b}Invert:@{ub} inverts the position of the elements, i.e. the element on the
  first postion is exchanged with the element on the last position,
  etc.
@{b}Shuffle:@{ub} is used for "mixing" the elements. Shuffling is done by
  exchanging two elements, respectively. A click on this gadget starts
  the shuffling process, which runs slowly at the beginning, with
  increasing speed. The exchanges are displayed. A faster shuffling
  process (no exchanges are shown) can be started by clicking the
  gadget with pressed shift key.
@{b}Range:@{ub} this indicates the maximum distance two elements may have in
  order to be exchanged while shuffling. E.g. a "1" means, that only
  adjacent elements can be exchanged. A "0" allows all elements to be
  exchanged.
@{b}Initialize:@{ub} this produces a sorted array with the desired shape (see
  below). If "stepped" is selected as shape, every click on this
  gadget increases the number of steps. You may as well decrease the
  number of steps by holding down the shift key while clicking.
@{b}Shape:@{ub} chooses the shape of the (sorted) elements in the sorting
  field. The selected shape is craeted by clicking on the Initialize-
  gadget.
  Possible shapes are:
  - @{i}straight:@{ui} produces a straight line, i.e. each element-value
      is unique (and equal to the element position).
  - @{i}parabolic:@{ui} produces a parabolic shape.
  - @{i}hyperbolic:@{ui} produces a hyperbolic shape.
  - @{i}sinusoidal:@{ui} produces a shape in form of a sinus oscillation.
  - @{i}stepped:@{ui} produces several steps (see above).
  - @{i}random:@{ui} each element obtains a random value.
@ENDNODE


@NODE "Terminating the program"
TERMINATING THE PROGRAM
=======================

Use the Exit-gadget or the close gadget of the window to terminate the
program.
@ENDNODE


